{{energy-stub}}

{{Infobox physical quantity
|bgcolour={default}
|name   = Specific mechanical energy
|image  =
|caption=
|unit   =  J/kg, or m<sup>2</sup>/s<sup>2</sup>
|symbols = e, or ε
|derivations = 
}}

'''Specific mechanical energy''' is the [[mechanical energy]] of an object per unit of mass. Similar to mechanical energy, the specific mechanical energy of an object in an isolated system subject only to [[Conservative force|conservative forces]] will remain constant.

It is defined as:

<math>\begin{align}
    e &= e_k+e_p
\end{align}</math>

where

* <math>e_k</math> is the [[specific kinetic energy]] 

* <math>e_p</math> it the [[specific potential energy]]

== Astrodynamics ==
{{Main article|Specific orbital energy}}In the [[gravitational two-body problem]], the specific mechanical energy <math>\epsilon</math> is given as:

<math>\begin{align}
  \epsilon &= \frac{v^2}{2} - \frac{\mu}{r}
            = -\frac{1}{2} \frac{\mu^2}{h^2} \left(1 - e^2\right)
            = -\frac{\mu}{2a}
\end{align}</math>

where

* <math>v\,\!</math> is the relative [[orbital speed]];
* <math>r\,\!</math> is the [[Orbital position vector|orbital distance]] between the bodies;
* <math>\mu = {G}(m_1 + m_2)\,\!</math> is the sum of the [[Standard gravitational parameter|standard gravitational parameters]] of the bodies;
* <math>h\,\!</math> is the [[specific relative angular momentum]] in the sense of [[relative angular momentum]] divided by the reduced mass;
* <math>e\,\!</math> is the [[Eccentricity (orbit)|orbital eccentricity]];
* <math>a\,\!</math> is the [[semi-major axis]].

=== Orbital Mechanics ===
When calculating the specific mechanical energy of a satellite in orbit around a celestial body, the mass of the satellite is assumed to be negligible:

<math>\mu = G(M + m) \approx GM</math>

where <math>M</math> is the mass of the celestial body.

